The Kepler-7 system, also known by alternative names KOI-97 and KIC 5780885, is located at a right ascension of 19 14 19.5623 and a declination of +41 05 23.3654. It lies approximately 948 ±21 parsecs, or 3090 ±69 light-years, from Earth. This system contains a single star with a mass of 1.32 ±0.09 solar masses and a radius of 1.96 ±0.07 solar radii, classified as a G0-type star with a temperature of 6027 ±75 K and a metallicity of 0.10 ±0.10. The Kepler-7 system hosts one confirmed planet, known by multiple names including 2MASS J19141956+4105233 b, KIC 5780885 b, KOI-97.01, and KOI-97 b. This planet has a mass of 0.44 ±0.04 Jupiter masses (140 ±13 Earth masses) and a radius of 1.620 ±0.010 Jupiter radii (18.16 ±0.11 Earth radii), orbiting its star every 4.89 days at a semi-major axis of 0.0625 AU with an eccentricity of 0.10. The planet’s equilibrium temperature is approximately 1487 K. Kepler-7 b was discovered in 2010 using the transit method, and the system’s data was last updated on 15/12/03. The system has been studied and catalogued by astronomers including Andrew Tribick, Hanno Rein, Marc-Antoine Martinod, and Ryan Varley.
A Kepler transit planet; explore its star–planet scale and orbit speed in the NASA Eyes 3D scene to see why many Kepler finds are short-period. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
Confirmed by Kepler using the transit method; the NASA viewer shows how orbital radius and star temperature combine to set equilibrium temperature. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

The Kepler-8 system, also referred to as KOI-10 and KIC 6922244, is positioned at a right ascension of 18 45 09.1489 and a declination of +42 27 03.8915. It is located approximately 1330 ±180 parsecs, or 4338 ±587 light-years, from Earth. This system contains a single F-type star with a mass of 1.13 +0.09 −0.10 solar masses and a radius of 1.45 +0.12 −0.13 solar radii, with a temperature of 6251 ±75 K and a metallicity of 0.05 ±0.09. Kepler-8 hosts one confirmed planet, known by multiple names including 2MASS J18450914+4227038 b, KIC 6922244 b, KOI-10.01, and KOI-10 b. The planet has a mass of 0.59 +0.13 −0.12 Jupiter masses (188 +41 −38 Earth masses) and a radius of 1.42 +0.05 −0.06 Jupiter radii (15.9 +0.6 −0.7 Earth radii), orbiting its star every 3.5225 days at a semi-major axis of 0.0483 +0.0006 −0.0012 AU with a circular orbit (eccentricity 0.00). Its equilibrium temperature is around 1520 K. Kepler-8 b was discovered in 2010 via the transit method, and the system’s information was last updated on 15/12/03. Astronomers who have contributed to its study include Andrew Tribick, Hanno Rein, Marc-Antoine Martinod, and Ryan Varley.

The Kepler-114 system, also known by alternative names KOI-156 and KIC 10925104, is situated at a right ascension of 19 36 29.1357 and a declination of +48 20 58.2910. It is located approximately 267 parsecs, or 871 light-years, from Earth. The system contains a single star with a mass of 0.71 ±0.02 solar masses, a radius of 0.67 ±0.04 solar radii, and a temperature of 4605 ±100 K. Kepler-114 hosts three confirmed planets, including Kepler-114 c, which was initially classified as a planet candidate but later validated with more than 99 percent confidence by a team at NASA Ames Research Center. Kepler-114 c, also known as KOI-156 c and Gaia DR2 2128939873302216320 c, has a radius of 0.137 ±0.008 Jupiter radii (1.53 ±0.09 Earth radii) and an orbital period of 8.0413 days. Many of its other physical parameters, including mass, semi-major axis, eccentricity, and equilibrium temperature, are still unknown. The planet was discovered in 2014 via the transit method, and the system’s data was last updated on 14/02/26. Researchers involved in the study of Kepler-114 include Andrew Tribick, Hanno Rein, and Ryan Varley.

The Kepler-23 system, also known by the alternative names KOI-168 and KIC 11512246, is located at a right ascension of 19 36 52.5355 and a declination of +49 28 45.2531. It lies approximately 865 parsecs, or 2820 light-years, from Earth. The system contains a single star with a mass of 1.19 ±0.13 solar masses, a radius of 1.55 ±0.05 solar radii, and a temperature of 5828 ±100 K. Kepler-23 hosts three confirmed planets, including Kepler-23 c, which was originally classified as a planet candidate but later validated with more than 99 percent confidence by a team at NASA Ames Research Center. Kepler-23 c, also known by names such as KOI-168 c and Gaia DR2 2135019107451751168 c, has a radius of 0.34 ±0.03 Jupiter radii (3.9 ±0.3 Earth radii), an orbital period of 10.7424 days, and an eccentricity of 0.02 +0.39 −0.02. Many of its physical parameters, including mass, semi-major axis, and equilibrium temperature, are still unknown. The planet was discovered in 2014 using the transit method, and the system’s data was last updated on 15/06/09. Researchers who have contributed to the study of Kepler-23 include Andrew Tribick, Hanno Rein, Marc-Antoine Martinod, Miguel De Val-Borro, and Ryan Varley.
